<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-02T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-02T10:00:00-05:00" n="210" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d210">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114A/5–245: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-02T16:00:00+01:00">May 2,
                                        1945—4 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received May 2—3:13 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2569. American Interests—Japan. Your 1222, March 26.<note n="37" xml:id="d210fn1">Not printed; it requested the latest available
                                    information regarding prisoner-of-war camps in or near Yokohama,
                                    Tokyo, Osaka, Kobe, and Nagoya (711.-94114A/3–2645).</note>
                                Swiss note April 30 states Swiss Legation Tokyo reports increasing
                                difficulties in obtaining authorization visit camps because of
                                bombardments in areas where camps located.<note n="38" xml:id="d210fn2">In telegram 3057, June 5, 7 p.m., the Minister
                                    in Switzerland reported that Mr. Gorgé, in continuing his
                                    efforts to obtain authorization to visit POW camps, had
                                    addressed an urgent letter to “Minister Tojo”
                                    (711.94114A/6–545), presumably Shigenori Togo who became
                                    Japanese Minister for Foreign Affairs on April 9, 1945.</note>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>